'''Brandon Erik Mechele''' (born 28 January 1993) is a Belgian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre back]] for [[Belgian Pro League]] side [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]] and the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium national team]].

==Club career==
[[File:Brandon Mechele Club Brugge.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Mechele warming up for [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]].]]

Mechele joined Club Brugge at the age of six, progressing through the youth teams before making his senior debut against [[KSC Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|KSC Lokeren]] in the [[Belgian Pro League]] play-offs in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clubbrugge.be/en/teams/a-kern/players/brandon-mechele|title=Brandon Mechele|access-date=16 May 2026|website=Club Brugge}}</ref> He became a regular starter for Brugge in the [[2013–14 Club Brugge KV season|2013–14 season]], making 28 appearances in all competitions. During the [[2014–15 Club Brugge KV season|2014–15 season]], Mechele scored his first goal in a 2–1 win over [[SV Zulte Waregem]] and won his first trophy after beating [[RSC Anderlecht]] in the final of the [[2014–15 Belgian Cup|Belgian Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sofoot.com/breves/le-club-bruges-remporte-la-coupe-de-belgique|title=Le Club Bruges remporte la Coupe de Belgique|language=French|date=23 March 2015|access-date=16 May 2026|website=So Foot}}</ref> The following season, Mechele played 18 matches as Brugge won the [[2015–16 Belgian Pro League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/player/stats/_/id/191222/brandon-mechele|title=Brandon Mechele Career Stats|access-date=16 May 2026|website=ESPN}}</ref>

After losing his place in the starting XI under coach [[Michel Preud'homme]], Mechele spent the second half of the [[2016–17 Belgian First Division A|2016–17 season]] on loan at [[Sint-Truidense VV]]. On his return to Brugge in 2017–18, Mechele played all 30 matches in the league and the ten play-off matches as the ''Blauw-Zwit'' won another [[List of Belgian football champions|Belgian championship]]. He went on to win three consecutive league titles between [[2019–20 Belgian First Division A|2019–20]] and [[2021–22 Belgian First Division A|2021–22]] as well as another title in [[2023–24 Belgian Pro League|2023–24]] and the [[2024–25 Belgian Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voetbalprimeur.be/nieuws/1694903/de-500-matchen-van-mechele-bij-club-brugge-in-vijf-sleutelmomenten.html|title=Van twijfelgeval naar jubilaris: 500 matchen van Mechele in vijf sleutelmomenten|date=24 September 2025|access-date=16 May 2026|language=Dutch|website=VoetbalPrimeur}}</ref>

On 20 August 2025, Mechele made his 500th appearance for Brugge in a match against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League qualifying|UEFA Champions League qualifying]], scoring the third goal of a 3–1 win in Glasgow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rtbf.be/article/500-matches-avec-bruges-et-un-but-d-anthologie-pour-brandon-mechele-on-a-calme-le-public-direct-11589508|title=500 matches with Brugge and a goal of anthology for Brandon Mechele: "We calmed the direct public"|language=French|date=20 August 2025|access-date=16 May 2026|website=RTBF}}</ref>

==International career==
Mechele earned his first full international call up when [[Roberto Martínez]] named him in the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] squad in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web 
|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/martinez-looks-to-freshen-up-belgian-squad_sto6959923/story.shtml
|title=Martinez looks to freshen up Belgian squad
|publisher=Euro Sport
|date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> He made his [[Belgium national football team]] debut on 13 October 2019 in a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group I|Euro 2020 qualifier]] against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] as a stoppage time substitute for [[Thomas Vermaelen]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=528918|title=Kazakhstan v Belgium game report|date=13 October 2019}}</ref>

On 18 November 2025, Mechele scored his first international goal in a 7–0 win over [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] during [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hln.be/rode-duivels/na-kazachstan-was-het-moeilijk-maar-we-zijn-samengebleven-rode-duivels-halen-uit-tegen-liechtenstein-en-hebben-wk-ticket-beet~aeb1c7a1/|title=“Na Kazachstan was het moeilijk, maar we zijn samengebleven”: Rode Duivels halen uit tegen Liechtenstein en hebben WK-ticket beet|date=19 November 2025|access-date=16 May 2026|language=Dutch|
website=Het Laatste Nieuws}}</ref>

On 15 May 2026, he was named in Belgium's squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/belgium-squad-garcia-lukaku-named|title=Lukaku among experienced names in Belgium squad|date=15 May 2026|access-date=16 May 2026|website=FIFA}}</ref>

